<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Spot Effect Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Places a small environmental effect at a fixed world position, such as a fountain, drip, smokestack, or chimney smoke.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Spot Effect Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Spot Effect</Bold> Event Point creates a focused environmental effect at one
        specific location. Unlike a general Visual Effect, it does not combine multiple effect flags.
        It chooses one spot effect type, then places that effect at the Event Point position.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Spot Effects are commonly used as scenery and atmosphere: water fountains, water drips,
        dark smokestack smoke, and light chimney smoke. They can be active from the start of the
        mission, or they can wait for mission logic before appearing.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Spot Effect for small fixed environmental particles. Use Visual Effect instead when you need flare, fire dome, shockwave, smoke trails, bonfire, or combined scripted spectacle.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Spot Effect uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Letter group and colour are useful when
        the Spot Effect belongs to a larger area setup, objective chain, or set of linked scenery
        effects.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position is the most important common property for Spot Effect. The effect is anchored to
        this world location, so place it exactly where water should emit, smoke should rise, or a
        drip should originate. Check the Y value carefully if the effect appears inside a wall,
        under the floor, or too high above the source object.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide whether the effect exists from mission start or appears later.
        <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> is the normal setup for permanent environmental
        effects. <Bold>Dependency</Bold> is used when the effect should start after another Event
        Point, such as a mission state change or scripted activation.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Spot Effect-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Spot Effect has two type-specific settings. <Bold>Data[0]</Bold> stores the selected spot
        effect type as an index into the Spot FX list. <Bold>Data[1]</Bold> stores the scale.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Effect Type</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Effect Type chooses the single Spot FX visual to place. The available types are:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Water Fountain</Bold> - a fixed fountain-style water effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Water Drip</Bold> - a smaller dripping water effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dark Smokestack Smoke</Bold> - darker smoke for industrial stacks or heavy smoke sources.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Light Chimney Smoke</Bold> - lighter smoke for chimneys and softer ambient smoke sources.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Scale</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Scale controls the size or strength of the spot effect and is clamped by the editor to
        <Bold>0-1024</Bold>. Most existing Spot Effects use <Bold>0</Bold> for default scale.
        Small non-zero values, such as <Bold>4</Bold> or <Bold>5</Bold>, are used in some missions
        for subtle adjustment.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Choose the effect type first, place it precisely, then adjust scale only if the default effect is visibly too small or too strong in context.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Spot Effects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Spot Effect usage is mostly environmental. The common trigger patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> - use for effects that should exist from mission start.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - use when another Event Point should enable the effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - the normal listening mode for permanent and one-shot activation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active While</Bold> - useful when the effect should remain tied to a condition instead of being a simple permanent activation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical placement detail:</Run>
                <Run> Spot Effects are fixed to their Event Point position. If the effect looks wrong, correct its position and altitude before changing trigger logic.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Spot Effect Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Always-On Chimney Smoke</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>None</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold> for chimney or smokestack effects that are
        part of the level atmosphere from the start of the mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Spot Effects <Bold>50-57</Bold> are
        <Bold>Light Chimney Smoke</Bold> entries using trigger <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode
        <Bold>Active</Bold>. They are placed as a set of ambient smoke points.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Add one Spot Effect per smoke source, choose <Bold>Light Chimney Smoke</Bold> or
        <Bold>Dark Smokestack Smoke</Bold>, leave the trigger as <Bold>None</Bold>, and place the
        point at the top of the chimney or stack.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Always-On Water Features</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Water Fountain</Bold> or <Bold>Water Drip</Bold> for decorative water sources or
        environmental detail that should be visible throughout the mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>BAALROG1.ucm</Bold>, Spot Effects <Bold>87</Bold> and <Bold>88</Bold> are
        <Bold>Water Fountain</Bold> entries with trigger <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode
        <Bold>Active</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place the Event Point at the fountain or drip source, choose the appropriate water effect,
        and test the altitude so the effect originates from the visible geometry rather than below
        or above it.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Dependency-Enabled Fountain Group</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when a fountain, drip, or other spot effect should appear only
        after another mission condition has fired. This is useful for toggled scenery, objective
        state changes, or scripted environmental reveals.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>botanic1.ucm</Bold>, Spot Effects <Bold>56-59</Bold> are
        <Bold>Water Fountain</Bold> effects and Spot Effect <Bold>60</Bold> is
        <Bold>Water Drip</Bold>. They all use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point
        <Bold>39</Bold>, so the group is controlled by the same mission condition.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create the Event Point that should control the effect group first. Add the Spot Effects,
        place each one at its source, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold>, and
        set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the controlling Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Condition-Linked Ambient Effect</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> when the effect should stay tied to a condition rather than
        simply becoming active once. This is useful when the engine should treat the effect as
        present only while its dependency remains valid.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>botanicc.ucm</Bold>, Spot Effects <Bold>56-59</Bold> are
        <Bold>Water Fountain</Bold> effects using <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point
        <Bold>39</Bold> with listening mode <Bold>Active While</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Small Scaled Adjustment</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use Scale sparingly for fine adjustment. Existing missions generally keep Spot Effects at
        default scale, with small non-zero values used only where the effect needs to read slightly
        differently in the scene.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>MIB.ucm</Bold>, Spot Effect <Bold>490</Bold> uses
        <Bold>Dark Smokestack Smoke</Bold> at <Bold>Scale 5</Bold>, while Spot Effect
        <Bold>498</Bold> uses <Bold>Water Drip</Bold> at <Bold>Scale 5</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Spot Effect Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide whether the effect is permanent scenery or controlled by mission logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Spot Effect</Bold> Event Point at the exact source location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the <Bold>Effect Type</Bold>: Water Fountain, Water Drip, Dark Smokestack Smoke, or Light Chimney Smoke.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Leave <Bold>Scale</Bold> at 0 unless the effect needs a visible size adjustment.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For permanent scenery, use <Bold>None</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For scripted scenery, use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the controlling Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the effect in context with nearby buildings, roofs, objects, and map altitude.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Group related Spot Effects by colour and letter when they belong to the same area or trigger chain.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> Effect Type is correct, Scale is intentional, the point is placed at the source, Y altitude is correct, and the trigger matches whether the effect is permanent or mission-controlled.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
